{
  "answer": "**In Cynewulf's *Juliana*, the caesura falls unusually early in line 25 (after the proper name \"Heliseus\"), creating a short a-verse of just one stressed word.**[^1]\n\nOld English alliterative verse typically places the caesura after two (sometimes three) stressed syllables in the a-verse, balancing it against a b-verse of similar stress pattern. Here, however, \"Heliseus\" stands alone before the caesura (\"Heliseus,        hæfde ealdordom micelne ond mærne\"), isolating the pagan reeve's name as a stark monosyllabic hammer-blow (stressed HE-li-SEUS, but emphatically front-loaded).\n\n**Rhetorically, this placement emphasizes the antagonist's identity while creating suspension**: the abrupt pause spotlights \"Heliseus\" as the embodiment of worldly power (\"hæfde ealdordom micelne ond mærne\"), heightening dramatic tension before revealing Juliana's spiritual superiority over such \"arleas\" authority. It mimics a theological pause, contrasting pagan dominion with divine truth, as the narrative pivots to her unyielding faith.[^1]\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Juliana*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-juliana-9a2157/1/original/#p-408b9f).",
